			<h1 class='intro__hed'>Around the World</h1>
			<p class='intro__dek'>A map from your doorstep, to the other side of the world, and back again.</p>
			<p class='intro__byline'>By
				<a href='http://dnewcomb.com' class="link-text" target='_blank'>
					<strong>David Newcomb</strong>
				</a>
			</p>
			<time class='intro__time'>June 2020</time>
			<div class='intro__prelude'>
                <p>
                    On June 14, 2020 in the middle of <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://oceanconservancy.org/blog/2020/05/26/celebrate-national-ocean-month-us/">Ocean Month</a>, U.S. explorer, oceanographer and astronaut <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathryn_D._Sullivan">Kathy Sullivan</a> hit an incredible milestone. As part of a research mission, she dove nearly 36,000 feet to the deepest point in the ocean: <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/astronaut-kathy-sullivan-challenger-deep-dive-scn/index.html">Challenger Deep</a>. Completing this dive is the ocean's extreme answer to summitting Mt. Everest, the highest point on Earth, standing at a formidable 29,000 ft. In completing her voyage, Kathy became the first and only person to both fly to the outermost reaches of space exploration and dive to its farthest depths.<br><br>

                    The scientific importance of her mission to collect samples from the seafloor highlights, as well, the crucial goals of Ocean Month: to promote sustainable ocean use and encourage ocean exploration. We have yet to observe nearly <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://www.livescience.com/14493-ocean-exploration-deep-sea-diving.html">95% of the ocean</a> or to classify <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/ocean-species.html">90% of ocean species</a>, making it Earth's last unexplored frontier. Discovering these new species could lead to untold beauty, appreciation, and innovation. Observing nature's ingenuity has led to beneficial advancements like <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://www.technologyreview.com/2008/03/06/221447/whale-inspired-wind-turbines/">whalefin-inspired wind turbines</a> and <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://www.wired.com/2005/03/shark-skin-inspires-ship-coating/">sharkskin-inspired ship coating</a> amongst many others.<br><br>

                    In honor of Ocean Month and Kathy's exploration, I spent some time virtually exploring the Earth. I collected land elevation data, ocean depth data, and international boundary data (see <a class="link-text" href="#appendix">Appendix</a>). I wanted to know what's on the <a class="link-text" target="_blank"  href="https://www.antipodesmap.com/">other side of the world</a>. I wanted to learn what it would be like to take a journey from my front door, up to the North Pole, down the opposite side to the South Pole, and back home again. This trip would represent the longest "straight line" trip I could take around the world. Mapping it out could show me which oceans I'd sail on and which nations I'd visit.<br><br>

                    Visually inspired by <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://www.reddit.com/r/westworld/comments/fw37d5/what_is_the_divergence_thing/">Westworld's divergence visualization</a>, I created a circular  visualization of Earth's elevation to help explore every slice of the world. Just type in any starting place below and start exploring!
        		</p>
