		<div class='intro' id="appendix" style="font-family: 'Avenir'">
			<h2>Appendix</h2>
			<p>The global elevation data above comes from <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/mgg/global/">NOAA</a>. To calculate elevation, they created a grid of the Earth and averaged elevation for each rectangle of the grid. They made the grid from 21,600 vertical slices of longitude (representing 1 <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minute_and_second_of_arc">arc-minute</a> each) and 10,800 horizontal slices of latitude. Due to the curvature of the Earth, these curved grid rectangles are approximately 1 mile by 1 mile at Equator, and like a thinning ribbon, they converge to 0 miles wide each of the poles.<br><br>

			Since each grid slice has width, at any given latitude-longitude point, there can be overlap between countries or maritime zones. For instance, half the width of a slice could be taken up by Nepal, and the other half could be taken up by China. In situations of overlap, I defaulted to show the country with a lower population count. On the flip side, for maritime overlap, I prioritized showing larger bodies of water since oceans are the article's primary focus.<br><br>

			Going back a moment though, how do we find intersections between these slices and countries/oceans in the first place? To find intersections, I started by finding <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shapefile">shapefiles</a>. In the geospatial world, shapefiles are file formats that outline the boundaries of any shape and often carry some metadata. I got maritime shapefile data from <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://www.marineregions.org/">Marine Regions</a> and country shapefile data from <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://www.naturalearthdata.com/downloads/10m-cultural-vectors/">Natural Earth</a>. After converting global elevation slices into shapefiles as well, I overlayed each slice on top of land and water files, found intersections and output combined data. After that, it was a matter of making the graph.<br><br>

			One interesting learning about maritime data was how far off the coast countries maintain economic autonomy (often 200 miles) as part of their <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exclusive_economic_zone#:~:text=An%20exclusive%20economic%20zone%20(EEZ,production%20from%20water%20and%20wind.">Exclusive Economic Zones</a>. I added these maritime zones as part of each country's territory, helping highlight island nations that may have otherwise appeared unfairly small in the circular visualization.<br><br>

			I'm also currently working on a <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://native-land.ca/territory-acknowledgement/">territory acknowledgment</a> article that can help highlight the native lands that modern countries occupy. For this article, I'm applying the same method above and using native territory shapefiles from the <a class="link-text" target="_blank" href="https://native-land.ca/">Native Land</a> project. The data is highly detailed for North America and Australia, but largely absent from other parts of the world, so I'm working to find other sources and help expand the Native Land repository.<br><br>
